Let  

a_n = (-1)^n \dfrac{n!}{n^{\,n}}, \qquad n=1,2,\dots  

1.  Absolute values  

|a_n| = \dfrac{n!}{n^{\,n}}.

2.  Apply the ratio test to the positive series Σ|a_n|.  
Compute the ratio of successive terms:

\frac{|a_{n+1}|}{|a_n|}
      =\frac{(n+1)!/(n+1)^{\,n+1}}{n!/n^{\,n}}
      =\frac{(n+1)\,n^{\,n}}{(n+1)^{\,n+1}}
      =\left(\frac{n}{n+1}\right)^{\!n}
      =\left(1-\frac1{n+1}\right)^{\!n}.

Take the limit:

\lim_{n\to\infty}\left(1-\frac1{n+1}\right)^{\!n}
      =\frac1e \;(<1).

Because the limit L = 1/e is strictly less than 1, the ratio test tells us that the series  

Σ_{n=1}^{\infty} |a_n| = Σ_{n=1}^{\infty} n!/n^{\,n}

converges.

3.  Absolute convergence ⇒ convergence  
Since the series of absolute values converges, the original alternating series converges absolutely.

Conclusion  
The series  

Σ_{n=1}^{\infty} (-1)^{n}\dfrac{n!}{n^{\,n}}

is convergent, and it is absolutely convergent.
